{"questionId":"25428","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>This question asks you to investigate conditions for the existence of complex roots of polynomial equations of degree <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">3</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">4</mtext></math>.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;<br>The cubic equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>∈</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>, has roots <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>β</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Noah believes that if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>≥</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>q</mi></math> then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>β</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi></math> are all real.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>By varying the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math> in the equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, determine the smallest positive integer value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math>&nbsp;required to show that Noah is incorrect.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>use of GDC (<em>eg</em> graphs or tables)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25428","referenceCode":"22M.3.AHL.TZ2.2e.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By varying the value of q in the equation x3-7x2+qx+1=0, determine the smallest positive integer value of q required to show that Noah is incorrect.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"e.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.14—Complex roots of polynomials, conjugate roots, De Moivre’s, powers & roots of complex numbers"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}